CCSDS 133.0 Space Packet framing — external-oracle reference
============================================================

ccsds_space_packet_reference.txt holds the byte-exact reference output for the
CCSDS Space Packet Protocol primary-header framing (6-octet primary header and
full encoded packet), computed by an independent third-party library and used to
externally validate kshana's own implementation (see
tests/ccsds_space_packet_reference.rs). These files are not part of the kshana
source and are not shipped in the published crates/packages.

Oracle
------
spacepackets 0.32.0 — an independent Python implementation of the CCSDS Space
Packet Protocol, CCSDS 133.0-B-2 (R. Mueller / us-irs, project us-irs/
spacepackets-py, Apache-2.0). Its `SpacePacketHeader.pack()` does its own
bit-packing of the 6-octet primary header per CCSDS 133.0-B-2 §4.1.3, its
`SpacePacketHeader.unpack()` parses it back, and `SpacePacket.pack()` appends the
user-data field. It shares no code with kshana, so its byte output is a genuine
external authority for the framing — the same library-vs-library style as DOP vs
gnss_lib_py and the trade kernels vs scipy.

What is compared (byte-exact, zero tolerance)
---------------------------------------------
The 6-octet primary header is an integer bit-packing (no floating point):

  word1 (bits) = version(3) | type(1) | sec-hdr-flag(1) | APID(11)
  word2 (bits) = seq-flags(2) | seq-count(14)
  word3        = packet-data-length(16) = (data-field octets) - 1

For each of the 33 field combinations the test compares, byte-for-byte:
  * HEADERHEX — kshana encode_packet(...)[..6]  vs  SpacePacketHeader.pack()
  * FULLHEX   — kshana encode_packet(...)        vs  SpacePacket.pack()
                (header + data; only for the shf=0, small-data cases — see below)
  * round-trip — kshana decode_packet(bytes) recovers every field
                 (matched independently against SpacePacketHeader.unpack())

The grid spans (planned coverage): version 0; TM and TC; SHF on/off; APID
{0,1,2,0x123,0x7FF}; all four sequence flags; seq-count {0,5,0x34,0x3FFF};
data-length-field {0,3,0x16,0xFFFF}; plus the all-zeros and all-ones saturated
sentinels. It includes the four worked examples from spacepackets-py's own test
suite / docs.

Scope and one deliberate asymmetry (honest)
-------------------------------------------
This validates the CCSDS-133.0 *primary-header framing* — the exact bit layout
and a round-trippable encode/decode — byte-for-byte. It does NOT validate
secondary-header content, CRC, segmentation re-assembly, or any conformance
certification beyond the framing (kshana's own module docs already scope these
out).

spacepackets refuses to pack a *full* packet when the secondary-header flag is
set but no secondary-header bytes are supplied; kshana models only the flag bit,
not the secondary-header content. So FULLHEX is '-' for the shf=1 cases (and for
the few cases with a data field > 0x16, kept small to bound the fixture size).
The secondary-header *flag bit* itself is still fully exercised by HEADERHEX and
by the round-trip field decode in every shf=1 case — only the (out-of-scope)
secondary-header *payload* is not framed.

Provenance / reproducibility
----------------------------
Generated by the committed generate_ccsds_space_packet_reference.py
(spacepackets 0.32.0, Python 3.14). Offline, no kshana code involved:

    python3 -m venv /tmp/spvenv
    /tmp/spvenv/bin/pip install spacepackets
    /tmp/spvenv/bin/python generate_ccsds_space_packet_reference.py \
        > ccsds_space_packet_reference.txt

Format
------
'#'-prefixed comments, then one line per case:
  CASE <name> | <tc> | <shf> | <apid> | <seqflags> | <seqcount> | <dlen_field> \
       | <HEADERHEX> | <FULLHEX-or-'-'>
where tc/shf are 0/1, seqflags is the 2-bit value (0 continuation, 1 first,
2 last, 3 unsegmented), HEADERHEX is the 12 hex chars of the 6 primary-header
octets, and FULLHEX is the full encoded packet's hex (or '-').
